05448nam a22005775i 9781800101838DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20212021xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97818001018387 a10.1515/97818001018382doi  a(DE-B1597)675118  a(OCoLC)1268256517  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 7aMUS0200002bisacsh04a782.2609/021 aBent, Margaret, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Dorset Rotulus :bContextualizing and Reconstructing the Early English Motet /cPeter M. Lefferts, Margaret Bent, Jared C. Hartt. 1aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (418 p.) :b6 colour, 24 b/w, 106 line illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures -- tList of Music Examples -- tList of Tables -- tAbbreviations -- tNote on the Transcriptions -- tIntroduction -- t1 The Source and its Contents -- t2 Contexts and Designs -- t3 Voice-Exchange Motets and Ascendenti sonet geminacio/ Viri Galilei -- t4 Margareta pascens oves and its Large-Scale Comparands -- t5 Rota versatilis: Towards a Reconstruction -- t6 The Curious Case of Regina preminencie/ Gemma nitens/ … mater es intacta -- t7 Introducing Naufragantes visita/ Navigatrix inclita/ T. Aptatur/ … velox perpetrat -- t8 The Musical Rotulus: Artifact, Image, and Attributes -- t9 Epilogue: Conclusions and Speculation -- tAppendix: Transcriptions, Texts, and Translations of the Four Dorset Motets -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Manuscripts -- tIndex of Musical Compositions -- tGeneral Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe exciting discovery of new music from the Middle Ages sheds new light on knowledge of the medieval motet.From its origins in the thirteenth century, the Latin-texted motet in England and France became the most significant and diverse polyphonic genre of the fourteenth, a body of music important both for its texts and its variety of musical structures. However, although the motet in England plays a vital role in the music-historical narrative of the first decades of the 1300s, it has too often been overlooked in modern scholarship, due largely to its preservation in numerous but almost entirely fragmentary sources.In 2017, substantial new fragments of medieval polyphony came to light. They originated at the Benedictine monastery of Abbotsbury, a major institution located high above Chesil Beach on Dorset's Jurassic Coast. The two leaves once headed an imposing musical scroll, and preserve significant portions of four large-scale Latin-texted motets from early fourteenth-century England. Discovery of this source brings to the fore a massive seven-section motet on St Margaret, hitherto known only through highly fragmentary snippets of two of its four voices, as well as a unicum with extraordinary features addressed to the Virgin Mary and St Nicholas. When coupled with the remaining motets, one on the Ascension and the other on the Virgin Mary, the Dorset motets expand our understanding of how the English developed their own approaches to the genre, forging styles and techniques quite independently of the continental norms against which earlier scholarship has judged (and sometimes demeaned) them.This book introduces the manuscript and its provenance in Abbotsbury, relates it to other scrolls of late medieval music, contextualizes its motets within the larger corpus of contemporary Latin-texted motets, and analyses and reconstructs each of the motets, providing complete performable transcriptions of three of these compositions as well as three of its large-scale comparands. Spurred by the Dorset discovery, this monograph, the first in thirty-five years devoted to the medieval motet in England, offers a new evaluation of the richness of the English repertory in its own terms.  aMode of access: Interne